# Supabase — Database Patterns Reference

---

## supabase-js Response Structure

Every supabase-js query returns the same structure. Know it to write correct error handling.

```typescript
const {
  data,       // query result — NULL when error occurs (not [] — NULL)
  error,      // null on success | { message, code, details, hint }
  count,      // row count — only populated with { count: 'exact' | 'planned' | 'estimated' }
  status,     // HTTP status code (200, 201, 204, 400, 401, 403, etc.)
  statusText  // HTTP status text ('OK', 'Not Found', etc.)
} = await supabase.from('orders').select('*', { count: 'exact' })

// error.code = PGRST error code (see rocket-supabase-api-keys.mdc)
// error.message = human readable message
// error.details = extra context (e.g., which constraint was violated)
// error.hint = suggested fix from PostgREST
```

### Always check error BEFORE accessing data

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG — crashes when data is null (on any error)
const orders = data.filter(o => o.status === 'pending')

// ❌ WRONG — hides errors silently
const orders = data || []

// ✅ CORRECT — explicit error check, then safe access
if (error) {
  console.error(`[${error.code}] ${error.message}`)
  return null
}
const orders = data ?? []  // data is guaranteed non-null after error check
```

### Getting row count
```typescript
// count is undefined unless you request it
const { data, count } = await supabase
  .from('orders')
  .select('*', { count: 'exact' })    // exact: full COUNT(*) — slower
  // count: 'planned'   — fast estimate from query planner
  // count: 'estimated' — fastest, least accurate

// Get count only (no row data) — fastest for pagination UI
const { count } = await supabase
  .from('orders')
  .select('*', { count: 'exact', head: true })  // head: true = no body returned
```

