## Joins — Embedded Foreign Key Selects

The most powerful and most misunderstood feature in supabase-js.

### One-to-many (user → orders)
```typescript
// Get user's orders with profile data
const { data } = await supabase
  .from('orders')
  .select(`
    id,
    amount,
    status,
    profiles (
      id,
      full_name,
      avatar_url
    )
  `)
  .eq('user_id', userId)

// data[0].profiles.full_name  ← direct access
```

### !inner — filter parent by child column
```typescript
// Only return orders that HAVE a matching payment record
// Without !inner: orders without payments are returned with payments = null
// With !inner: orders without payments are excluded entirely
const { data } = await supabase
  .from('orders')
  .select('*, payments!inner(id, status)')
  .eq('payments.status', 'succeeded')
```

### Many-to-many (posts ↔ tags via junction table)
```sql
-- Junction table
CREATE TABLE post_tags (
  post_id UUID REFERENCES posts(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
  tag_id  UUID REFERENCES tags(id)  ON DELETE CASCADE,
  PRIMARY KEY (post_id, tag_id)
);
```
```typescript
// Query — supabase handles the junction automatically
const { data } = await supabase
  .from('posts')
  .select('id, title, tags(id, name)')

// data[0].tags = [{ id: '...', name: 'nextjs' }, ...]
```

### Nested selects with filters
```typescript
const { data } = await supabase
  .from('profiles')
  .select(`
    id,
    full_name,
    orders (
      id,
      amount,
      status
    )
  `)
  .eq('orders.status', 'pending')   // filter on nested table
  .order('created_at', { foreignTable: 'orders', ascending: false })
```

